Lead Advanced Analytics and People Analytics at AT&T. And Liz, I'd love to have you kick us off

00:03:12.160 --> 00:03:18.720
here and share with us a little bit about your role, introduce yourself, but also share something

00:03:18.720 --> 00:03:24.800
you like to do outside of work too. Okay. Well, thank you, Rachel. And thanks for inviting me

00:03:24.800 --> 00:03:33.440
to be here this week. My role is I'm a data scientist on the People Analytics team at AT&T.

00:03:34.399 --> 00:03:42.399
And our focus in People Analytics is that we use data and insights gained from that data to

00:03:42.399 --> 00:03:50.559
help make business decisions regarding employees, work, and business objectives to try and improve

00:03:50.559 --> 00:03:58.399
the environment, improve business outcomes for the company. And something that I enjoy doing

00:03:58.399 --> 00:04:04.559
outside of work, I am an avid photographer and mostly nature photography and love visiting the

00:04:04.559 --> 00:04:11.759
local gardens or various areas around the Southeastern US and taking pictures, landscapes,

00:04:11.759 --> 00:04:17.119
wildlife, whatever I can find that's interesting. It's a lot of fun and very relaxing for me.

00:04:17.920 --> 00:04:25.359
I love it. Well, thank you so much for taking the time to join us today, Liz. As we get some

00:04:25.359 --> 00:04:31.679
questions coming in from everybody here, I'd love to just learn a little bit more about your

00:04:31.679 --> 00:04:36.079
journey into the field of People Analytics. I know I got to hear some of that when you spoke

00:04:36.079 --> 00:04:40.640
at a meetup a few years ago, but I think it'd be really interesting for everybody here too.

00:04:41.440 --> 00:04:50.720
Sure. I originally started working in the banking industry where I built a lot of my data analysis

00:04:50.720 --> 00:05:00.559
skills and joined an HR team in Bell South, which eventually became merged with AT&T a little over

00:05:00.559 --> 00:05:08.799
20 years ago and was primarily hired to do data analytics. They were building their

00:05:09.519 --> 00:05:17.600
their staffing organization. Back then, data analysis in HR was fairly new,

00:05:17.600 --> 00:05:24.640
at least at that company. Since then, I've moved into various roles and spent some time working

00:05:24.640 --> 00:05:33.519
as a project manager serving as a liaison between HR and IT as they were building tools for us so

00:05:33.600 --> 00:05:41.600
that our HR professionals could develop reports. From there, I eventually decided,

00:05:41.600 --> 00:05:46.239
or as I was learning, more and more companies were getting involved in doing predictive analytics

00:05:46.239 --> 00:05:51.920
in HR and how it could be applied. I decided to go back to school and get my master's degree in

00:05:51.920 --> 00:05:58.959
data science and have graduated about six or seven years ago and have been applying those

00:05:58.959 --> 00:06:06.399
skills at work ever since then. Awesome. How did you make the decision to

00:06:06.399 --> 00:06:11.679
then go back and get your master's? I had reached a point in my career where

00:06:11.679 --> 00:06:19.519
I was ready for a new challenge and was looking for what did I want to do next. At the same time,

00:06:20.160 --> 00:06:25.920
I like to stay informed of what's going on in the industry in general. I read a lot of news articles

00:06:25.920 --> 00:06:31.839
and attended a few conferences where I saw more and more companies were discussing the need to

00:06:31.839 --> 00:06:38.640
apply predictive analytics. I read a book by Eric Siegel where he presented a case study of a company

00:06:38.640 --> 00:06:44.880
that applied it to help reduce employee attrition in a business unit that had a very high attrition

00:06:44.880 --> 00:06:50.959
rate for employees, those leaving the company, that is. I was fascinated with the concept,

00:06:50.959 --> 00:06:58.239
did a little more research, started checking into programs, and decided on a master's degree program

00:06:59.040 --> 00:07:02.720
through Northwestern University, which fit my schedule perfectly,

00:07:02.720 --> 00:07:09.279
and worked on the degree in the evenings while I was working full-time during the day.

00:07:11.760 --> 00:07:19.679
Wow, that's impressive. I see a few Northwestern alums, it seems, in the chat as well. Abigail,

00:07:19.760 --> 00:07:24.320
if you had a follow-up question here on the master's program, you want to jump in?

00:07:24.320 --> 00:07:28.079
Yeah, so you mentioned scheduling, that it's around your schedule. What else were you, like,

00:07:28.079 --> 00:07:31.679
what criteria were you looking at when you were, when you knew you wanted a master's and you were

00:07:31.679 --> 00:07:40.160
trying to pick? I was, at the time, there were not a lot of programs available and I found a few

00:07:40.160 --> 00:07:45.839
universities, I think only four maybe, that were offering an online program that I could do

00:07:45.839 --> 00:07:52.880
remotely. And the local Atlanta universities did not have programs like that at the time.

00:07:52.880 --> 00:08:00.559
I believe Georgia Tech now does have one. So, one, I needed something with the flexibility so that I

00:08:00.559 --> 00:08:06.799
could do the classes in the evening while working full-time, and that was, narrowed it down

00:08:06.799 --> 00:08:12.799
tremendously in terms of which universities offered those types of programs. And from there,

00:08:13.519 --> 00:08:18.079
just researching, checking into what types of classes were included in each, I knew I wanted

00:08:18.079 --> 00:08:25.600
some hands-on experience, programming, and just looking at class offerings and considering

00:08:26.399 --> 00:08:30.720
the different university programs from there and just narrowed it down that way.

00:08:32.159 --> 00:08:38.799
Now, I think there's a lot more courses available through organizations like Coursera and Udemy,

00:08:39.520 --> 00:08:47.280
and those were not available back then, but there's a much wider range of opportunities for

00:08:47.280 --> 00:08:53.359
people who want to learn data science. And there was, at the time, I think that was in 2013, 2014

00:08:53.359 --> 00:09:03.359
is when I started my degree. Thank you. I saw in the chat a few comments about the PositCom

00:09:03.359 --> 00:09:08.559
background I have here. I'll put it in the chat if anybody wants it and wants to help

00:09:08.559 --> 00:09:17.599
promote the conference, feel free. But Liz, I think to maybe put us all in your shoes and kind

00:09:17.599 --> 00:09:22.239
of understand some of the problems you're working on a daily basis, would you be able to walk us

00:09:22.239 --> 00:09:31.359
through an example use case of analytics on the People Analytics team? Sure. Many cases,

00:09:32.159 --> 00:09:40.320
we work closely with business unit leaders, and we also have HR business partners who serve as the

00:09:40.320 --> 00:09:47.200
liaison between HR and each of our business units. So they'll typically come to us with a business

00:09:47.200 --> 00:09:54.159
question that needs to be solved, or we may identify on our own a business problem and do

00:09:54.159 --> 00:09:59.280
the research and analysis ourselves. But some of the cases where we apply analytics would be

00:09:59.359 --> 00:10:05.760
reducing employee attrition, trying to find ways that for teams that have a high attrition rate,

00:10:05.760 --> 00:10:11.760
find out what are the aspects of the job or the work environment, or even the external labor

00:10:11.760 --> 00:10:17.840
market that could be affecting or making our employees more likely to leave the company,

00:10:17.840 --> 00:10:23.200
and figure out from there, what can we change to help improve things and reduce that attrition

00:10:23.200 --> 00:10:29.280
rate? Because it is very expensive for companies to train employees and replace them on a regular

00:10:29.280 --> 00:10:35.119
basis. And another area, I've done a lot of forecasting. So if you're thinking about getting

00:10:35.119 --> 00:10:42.159
into People Analytics, time series forecasting is a very good skill to learn. And I've done

00:10:42.159 --> 00:10:49.039
forecasting to try and determine what our future attrition rates would be, estimating how our

00:10:49.039 --> 00:10:57.679
workforce will change in the future in terms of headcount, looking at skills and demand, and

00:10:57.679 --> 00:11:03.919
trying to figure out what changes do we need to make to the workforce as the company

00:11:03.919 --> 00:11:08.880
is making changes to our product portfolio and making future plans. And we do a little bit of

00:11:08.880 --> 00:11:13.760
forecasting two or three years into the future to try and give them some numbers to help estimate

00:11:13.760 --> 00:11:20.479
what's going on there. And another for employee surveys, there's a lot of need to

00:11:21.280 --> 00:11:26.559
analyze comments that employees enter in those surveys. So we've done a lot of text analytics

00:11:26.559 --> 00:11:27.359
there as well.

00:11:29.760 --> 00:11:36.880
Nice. Thank you. I see a few questions coming in here in the chat. And Saul, I think you had a

00:11:36.880 --> 00:11:41.520
question around like maybe ROI of People Analytics. Do you want to jump in there?

00:11:42.159 --> 00:11:43.200
Yeah. Can you guys hear me?

00:11:44.080 --> 00:11:44.960
Yes, I can.

00:11:44.960 --> 00:11:45.599
Yes.

00:11:45.599 --> 00:11:51.039
Great. Thanks, Liz. Appreciate the insights. I think, yeah, I'm curious as far as, you know,

00:11:51.039 --> 00:11:57.039
I work in finance. A lot of our analytics has to be around ROI and dollar cost. How do you and team

00:11:57.039 --> 00:12:03.119
go around like identifying those numbers? So when you say it's expensive to hire and train, you know,

00:12:03.119 --> 00:12:08.400
how detailed do you get? What's that process look like? And then, you know, when you see maybe a

00:12:08.400 --> 00:12:14.159
metric associated with attrition go down, like, you know, turnover retention is down. How do you

00:12:14.159 --> 00:12:18.080
then go back to your stakeholders and show those cost savings? Thank you.

00:12:18.799 --> 00:12:25.840
Oh, good question. We can get into a lot of detail in terms of determining how much it costs

00:12:25.840 --> 00:12:32.320
to hire and train a new employee. And it varies from job to job. So we need to look at each type

00:12:32.320 --> 00:12:38.000
of job and how long they spend in training. How long does it take them once they finish training?

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:41.760
How long does it take them to get up to speed to a more experienced employee?

00:12:42.479 --> 00:12:48.000
And in terms of filling the job, we also look at the cost of advertising that job,

00:12:48.640 --> 00:12:53.280
interviewing candidates, time spent interviewing those candidates and so forth.

00:12:53.280 --> 00:13:00.880
And all of that can be added together to determine what is the cost to hire and replace a typical

00:13:00.880 --> 00:13:07.039
employee for a specific type of job. From there, once we determine how much we've been able to

00:13:07.039 --> 00:13:14.479
reduce our attrition rate, we can go back to that cost of hire number and estimate a cost savings

00:13:14.479 --> 00:13:20.719
by reducing the attrition. And that's how we figure out the ROI for some of our projects.

00:13:23.520 --> 00:13:24.159
Thank you so much.

00:13:25.760 --> 00:13:32.479
I see Rob has a follow-up question, I think, on this piece too. And Rob, I'd be really curious

00:13:32.559 --> 00:13:36.799
to hear what this SCR is as well, if you want to jump in.

00:13:38.880 --> 00:13:40.400
Sure thing. Can you hear me?

00:13:41.200 --> 00:13:41.760
I can.

00:13:42.320 --> 00:13:43.200
Can you see me?

00:13:43.919 --> 00:13:44.400
I can.

00:13:44.880 --> 00:13:52.400
All right. We're functioning on a Thursday. Yeah. I am trained in IO psychology, PhD,

00:13:52.400 --> 00:13:57.679
and then I've dabbled in data science as well, but have recently come into this data storytelling

00:13:57.760 --> 00:14:04.479
realm. And I've stumbled across the McKinsey way of doing this called Situation Complication

00:14:04.479 --> 00:14:12.719
Resolution, and was just wondering if you had something similar as far as how do you get the

00:14:13.280 --> 00:14:18.400
executives engaged in what you're doing for the organization and really kind of drive home

00:14:18.400 --> 00:14:19.919
the impact that you're having?

00:14:20.880 --> 00:14:25.840
Well, that's a good question. And it varies from project to project. Sometimes if the

00:14:25.840 --> 00:14:32.239
executives come to us asking us to help them with data analysis to solve a problem, it's

00:14:32.239 --> 00:14:38.799
much easier to get their support and buy in on those projects. In other cases, we've gone to

00:14:38.799 --> 00:14:45.200
them and said, here, we've done this analysis and we've determined, and I'm not familiar with the

00:14:45.280 --> 00:14:51.280
SCR template that McKinsey has specifically, but I think it's kind of similar to what we do. We

00:14:51.280 --> 00:14:56.960
describe the situation, what business problem were we trying to solve, what were some of the key

00:14:56.960 --> 00:15:02.400
insights that we found that could help solve that problem and make some recommendations. And then

00:15:02.400 --> 00:15:08.799
it's up to the business leaders to decide which of those solutions they want to implement.

00:15:10.239 --> 00:15:10.960
Excellent. Thank you.

00:15:11.119 --> 00:15:17.840
Thank you. I see Kyle asked a question a bit earlier. I see stars next to it. So as a reminder,

00:15:17.840 --> 00:15:22.159
if it's something you want me to read out loud instead for you, just put a little asterisk next

00:15:22.159 --> 00:15:29.200
to it. But Liz, since you've been in data science for 10 plus years, what do you use or recommend

00:15:29.200 --> 00:15:35.119
to stay up to date with the latest tools or methods? Do you find any particular tool or method

00:15:35.119 --> 00:15:40.960
recommend to stay up to date with the latest tools or methods? Do you find any particular

00:15:40.960 --> 00:15:49.760
challenges? Challenging staying up to date with all the R packages. Heidiverse did not exist back

00:15:49.760 --> 00:15:56.719
when I was working on my master's program. So I've been trying to learn that and incorporate

00:15:57.520 --> 00:16:03.200
those packages into my work. And that makes it much easier. And I'm writing far less lines of

00:16:03.200 --> 00:16:12.159
code on my projects now. But as far as how I stay up to date, YouTube videos are often very helpful.

00:16:12.880 --> 00:16:17.919
I keep up with a lot of, I have a large collection of books now on R programming

00:16:17.919 --> 00:16:24.400
to help me stay up to date there. These days with people analytics, I've gotten to the point

00:16:24.400 --> 00:16:29.599
where I have LinkedIn connections that share news on what's happening in people analytics and the

00:16:29.599 --> 00:16:35.039
latest trends there and try to stay up to date that way with what's going on in our industry in

00:16:35.039 --> 00:16:42.239
general as well. And those are, I think just a few of them. Attending webinars, attending events like

00:16:42.239 --> 00:16:47.039
the data science hangout where somebody will mention something new that they're trying and I

00:16:47.039 --> 00:16:55.200
may do a little research on the web on that as well. Great, thank you. Thanks for the hangout

00:16:55.200 --> 00:17:03.440
shout out as well. Abigail asked, are the surveys you mentioned anonymous? Are they all text or do

00:17:03.440 --> 00:17:10.000
you also analyze in-person exit interviews? Curious about the data used in analyzing factors

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:18.160
affecting attrition. We do have exit interviews that are answered separately from some of our

00:17:18.880 --> 00:17:24.160
corporate surveys. We have a regular survey that we do to just measure what's the general

00:17:24.160 --> 00:17:29.520
attitude of our employees. And it consists of a combination of questions that have a

00:17:30.719 --> 00:17:37.199
agree to disagree Likert scale. And there's usually maybe one or two questions that just

00:17:37.199 --> 00:17:45.760
have an open-ended, please tell us about whatever the executives in the company decide is key point.

00:17:47.199 --> 00:17:51.680
It just allows the employees to type in whatever comments they want and from there we try and

00:17:51.680 --> 00:17:59.040
extract some of the common themes that show up in those comments. And as far as analyzing

00:17:59.040 --> 00:18:05.920
other items related to attrition, we may look at unemployment rates, anything that we can find in

00:18:05.920 --> 00:18:11.119
the labor market from US census data that we think might be helpful for that specific project.

00:18:11.760 --> 00:18:17.599
As well as looking, talking with our business unit, developing a good relationship with the

00:18:17.599 --> 00:18:24.000
business leaders for the area of concern helps tremendously because then we can get insights

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:30.319
from them on things that they are observing or that they feel might be a factor in causing

00:18:30.319 --> 00:18:37.439
attrition. And we work on finding what data can we get that backs that up and then do the analysis

00:18:37.439 --> 00:18:42.800
and try and determine does the data really show that what you believe is happening is truly

00:18:42.800 --> 00:18:50.640
happening. And that often helps. Sometimes we may dispel some myths and sometimes the data

00:18:50.640 --> 00:18:57.359
fully supports what they suspected. What's one of those myths? Can you share that with us?

00:18:59.920 --> 00:19:06.479
Probably not. Okay, no worries. Yeah, there's many times where people think

00:19:06.479 --> 00:19:12.000
something may be causing employees to leave but we just can't find data to support it.

00:19:12.479 --> 00:19:20.880
Yeah. Greg, I see you had a question a bit earlier here. I noticed my virtual background

00:19:20.880 --> 00:19:28.319
keeps making my arm disappear here. Greg, do you want to jump in? Yeah, absolutely. Thanks for being

00:19:28.319 --> 00:19:35.680
here today. I actually also used to work for AT&T. I came on board as part of the DirecTV

00:19:35.680 --> 00:19:40.959
acquisition years ago. And then like another person mentioned, I'm now in finance working

00:19:40.959 --> 00:19:47.199
with Schwab. But one of the things that I found a struggle when we were acquired by AT&T, you know,

00:19:47.199 --> 00:19:52.560
our company was around 15,000. And when we joined AT&T, we just immediately jumped up to like

00:19:52.560 --> 00:19:58.959
300,000 employees as part of AT&T. So keeping up with the larger data and analytics community

00:20:00.239 --> 00:20:06.479
was a really tough task, like knowing who is doing what and where data was and how to access

00:20:06.479 --> 00:20:13.359
things. And I was wondering if you have any advice on how your team kind of networks across

00:20:13.359 --> 00:20:23.280
a large organization like that? A lot of it is through knowing the right contacts. And our AVP

00:20:23.839 --> 00:20:31.599
does a really good job at marketing the team, I guess you could say, talking to other leaders

00:20:31.599 --> 00:20:36.959
within HR and even within the business units to let them know our team does exist and we're

00:20:36.959 --> 00:20:46.479
available to help them. As far as finding data for our HR professionals, we have a centralized system

00:20:46.479 --> 00:20:52.959
that we encourage everybody to use to get employee data to answer most of their common questions that

00:20:52.959 --> 00:20:58.400
they have. And that way everybody has one version of the truth. Everybody's numbers are matching

00:20:58.400 --> 00:21:03.760
from one report to the next and so forth. But then, of course, there's other systems such as

00:21:03.760 --> 00:21:09.599
our finance department has their own data sets that are more focused on the financial metrics

00:21:09.599 --> 00:21:15.280
of the company and budget metrics. And each business unit has different performance metrics

00:21:15.280 --> 00:21:22.319
that they measure for employees. And it's oftentimes trying to find the right contact person

00:21:22.319 --> 00:21:29.520
in order to figure out who is the right person to talk to to get access to that data and learn

00:21:29.520 --> 00:21:35.520
more about what's in that database. But I guess you could say a lot of networking

00:21:35.520 --> 00:21:42.000
is involved is probably the best way to go about it. Awesome. I appreciate that. Thank you.

00:21:44.400 --> 00:21:50.319
And on this topic, Liz, maybe it'd be helpful to also chat a little bit about the data,

00:21:50.319 --> 00:21:56.959
the HR analytics and data science community of practice. I noticed that on your LinkedIn. I was

00:21:56.959 --> 00:22:02.640
just curious to know a little bit more about that group and how often you meet as well.

00:22:04.239 --> 00:22:09.359
We just started the group in January and we have not had our first meeting yet.

00:22:10.079 --> 00:22:18.160
But we've created a virtual environment in Viva Engage. And each week I've been sharing

00:22:18.160 --> 00:22:23.439
different news tips with the members of the community. When we started it,

00:22:25.760 --> 00:22:33.199
the idea was we wanted it to be a community where people who knew nothing about analytics and had no

00:22:33.199 --> 00:22:39.520
experience could just start from the very beginning and understand what is it that we do in analytics

00:22:39.520 --> 00:22:46.319
and how do we apply this to HR problems and solving those types of problems. So I started

00:22:46.800 --> 00:22:52.640
from the very beginning about sharing articles, sharing YouTube videos. I just do a little

00:22:52.640 --> 00:22:59.839
research to try and find something that's pertinent and relevant that HR people can relate to

00:23:00.400 --> 00:23:06.400
and share something new each week in short videos. Everybody typically has very busy schedules,

00:23:06.400 --> 00:23:12.239
so I'm trying to also keep in mind that they may not have time for a learning course that

00:23:12.239 --> 00:23:18.239
takes several hours, but spending 30 minutes watching a video to learn something new each week,

00:23:18.239 --> 00:23:25.199
they seem to appreciate that and it helps keep them up to date. So we've been gradually increasing

00:23:25.199 --> 00:23:30.560
and getting into more complex topics including things such as how do you present your results

00:23:30.560 --> 00:23:38.239
of your analysis project to an executive, doing exploratory data analysis, typical

00:23:39.040 --> 00:23:44.319
what are the key analytic skills that people might want to learn from the very beginner to

00:23:44.319 --> 00:23:49.199
more experienced and even to more advanced and where could they learn those skills.

00:23:50.959 --> 00:23:54.959
We are planning in the second quarter of this year to start doing some meetings

00:23:54.959 --> 00:24:00.000
and I will be contacting some of our community members to get some feedback from them

00:24:00.000 --> 00:24:05.040
on whether they would prefer an open question answer format similar to this or would they want

00:24:05.040 --> 00:24:12.160
formal presentations or maybe we'll alternate between those. But it's been, I guess we're in

00:24:12.160 --> 00:24:16.719
the very early stages and in talking to other people that have started communities, I've learned

00:24:16.719 --> 00:24:20.640
most of the participants are kind of shy, so we haven't gotten to that point where there's a lot

00:24:20.640 --> 00:24:28.000
of back and forth conversation going on yet, but I do get emails and comments from people

00:24:28.000 --> 00:24:32.560
telling me they appreciate what's been shared and they're learning something new, so I do like

00:24:32.560 --> 00:24:36.640
that fact, as long as they're learning something new. But we have, what's been challenging is we

00:24:36.640 --> 00:24:42.000
have members that are across the board in terms of their analytic skills, so I try and alternate

00:24:42.000 --> 00:24:47.680
between sharing something more advanced and sharing something for those that are at

00:24:47.680 --> 00:24:54.800
the beginner entry level. I love that. Well, I'm excited to hear more about the group as you

00:24:54.800 --> 00:25:00.880
go as well. Is that just in AT&T or is that external? It's just within AT&T. Okay.

00:25:02.319 --> 00:25:06.319
Joy, I see you just put a question into the chat. Do you want to jump in here next?

00:25:08.000 --> 00:25:14.400
Hi, sure, yeah. First time caller. Thanks for joining us. Nice to meet you.

00:25:15.359 --> 00:25:20.239
Nice to meet everyone as well. I was just curious, you didn't mention this, but I would

00:25:20.239 --> 00:25:26.239
be curious whether your team is involved in using data for hiring or promotion decisions,

00:25:27.040 --> 00:25:32.800
and especially how you finesse potential conflicts between ideas of fit or the right

00:25:32.800 --> 00:25:39.280
quote-unquote type of person versus the sort of benefits of diversity or the potential issues of

00:25:39.280 --> 00:25:46.319
bias. One of the things I think is so great about data is we can use it to expand stakeholders'

00:25:46.319 --> 00:25:53.920
thinking, but I know that sometimes it's a little tricky. Yeah, and our team does not get into

00:25:55.119 --> 00:25:59.359
the details of making recommendations about individual employees, but we have done

00:26:00.000 --> 00:26:06.880
some diversity analysis in general, and I'm trying to think. I personally have not worked

00:26:06.880 --> 00:26:12.400
on a project related specifically to promotions or hiring, but we do have some other members of

00:26:12.479 --> 00:26:18.640
our team that have been doing analysis related to those, and so I may not be able to provide you much

00:26:19.199 --> 00:26:25.760
in the way of details on those, but it is a careful balance, but at the same time,

00:26:28.000 --> 00:26:34.239
you still have to. We use data to try and help support those decisions, but at the same time,

00:26:35.199 --> 00:26:41.760
there are the individual hiring manager and the folks in our talent acquisition team get more

00:26:41.760 --> 00:26:47.680
involved in making those decisions when it comes to the individual employees in each individual

00:26:47.680 --> 00:26:58.319
job opening. Great, thank you so much. Thank you. Yeah, and if anybody listening in today

00:26:58.319 --> 00:27:04.959
wants to put into the chat their own thoughts there too, it sounds like there's some interest

00:27:04.959 --> 00:27:11.520
in connecting with other people analytics folks, so I was trying to at the same time go grab

00:27:11.520 --> 00:27:16.640
the link of a group from one of our other Hangout attendees, but I will get that one again.

00:27:17.839 --> 00:27:26.959
I see Ethan had a question a little bit earlier. Liz, have LLMs changed your,

00:27:26.959 --> 00:27:31.599
and when I say, I try and be better about acronyms, have large language models changed

00:27:31.599 --> 00:27:38.560
your approach to text analysis? If so, how have you incorporated them into text analysis workflows?

00:27:38.959 --> 00:27:47.520
Yes, it has. We have a large language model in AT&T that's protected behind our firewall

00:27:47.520 --> 00:27:54.239
so that our employees do not have a risk of sharing any proprietary data with any external

00:27:54.800 --> 00:28:02.800
LLM tools, and I've found recently there was a survey that was done after an event. They wanted

00:28:02.800 --> 00:28:07.359
to get some feedback from the participants and had some open-ended questions in there,

00:28:07.359 --> 00:28:13.839
and I chose to use our internal LLM model and gave it all of the comments from the employees

00:28:13.839 --> 00:28:19.520
and asked it to give me some summaries, and by interacting with the LLM and asking it different

00:28:19.520 --> 00:28:25.280
questions, I was able to summarize those comments much faster than I would have using some of the

00:28:25.280 --> 00:28:31.040
traditional methods that I was using in R, so now that's become my go-to tool in analyzing comments.

00:28:31.359 --> 00:28:37.359
Abigail, I think you had a follow-up on this question. Is it, you said, is it OpenAI and

00:28:37.359 --> 00:28:40.959
Azure, or is it something like Bedrock, or is it open source? Do you know?

00:28:43.359 --> 00:28:49.199
It's, I don't know if it's open source tool, but it's one where our data and artificial

00:28:49.199 --> 00:28:56.479
intelligence team, which is a separate team from mine, they implemented it, and it is an internal

00:28:56.479 --> 00:29:04.719
tool that's available only to AT&T employees. Okay, cool. Thank you.

00:29:07.920 --> 00:29:12.560
Thank you. Nolan, I see you asked a question here. Want to go next?

00:29:14.079 --> 00:29:20.160
Yeah, sure. You know, Liz, I was curious how maybe you all are balancing like confidentiality

00:29:20.160 --> 00:29:26.479
levels within employee surveys and then integrating that into your models or any

00:29:26.479 --> 00:29:32.880
analytics. I know at times it's hard to make that balance and do like, you know, collect data at the

00:29:32.880 --> 00:29:38.880
individual level and then have access to that while also balancing those confidentiality thresholds.

00:29:38.880 --> 00:29:47.680
Any thoughts on that? There, we have a team of IO psychologists, industrial organizational

00:29:47.680 --> 00:29:53.920
psychologists, that manage a lot of our surveys, and some of those surveys are done through

00:29:53.920 --> 00:29:59.040
vendors, and it depends on the situation. Sometimes they are completely anonymous where

00:29:59.040 --> 00:30:05.359
we have no ability to get that data, and sometimes we might be able to get that data

00:30:05.359 --> 00:30:13.280
in order to match things up at an aggregate level. We never report at an individual employee's

00:30:14.000 --> 00:30:19.439
information of what they responded to in a survey, but we can report it at an aggregate level

00:30:19.439 --> 00:30:24.959
for an entire department once it meets a minimum threshold in terms of responses.

00:30:27.439 --> 00:30:33.760
Great, thank you. I see a follow-up on the text analysis discussion.

00:30:34.560 --> 00:30:36.640
James Yu, do you want to jump in here?

00:30:41.920 --> 00:30:48.319
Hi Elizabeth, this is James. I'm over at Guess supporting data science and analytics, and one of

00:30:48.319 --> 00:30:54.560
the questions I had was for the sentiment analysis that you've been doing based on

00:30:56.000 --> 00:31:01.760
text data, and I understand there's a lot of data mining that's involved within the customer

00:31:01.760 --> 00:31:11.439
surveys. My question is, as you're creating this sentiment label, if you will, to classify to

00:31:11.439 --> 00:31:14.400
different levels of the sentiment in which you're seeing for these

00:31:16.479 --> 00:31:24.479
employees, how do you train your data to label someone as seeing someone who is dissatisfied or

00:31:24.479 --> 00:31:29.599
understanding that someone who is content with their work? That's got to be very difficult to

00:31:29.599 --> 00:31:36.319
understand context, so I'm wondering how does your team resolve it to the level of context of which

00:31:38.160 --> 00:31:42.560
the employee is speaking to, and how do you label it properly?

00:31:44.640 --> 00:31:49.520
What we found in our questions is it's very hard due to the way our questions are worded.

00:31:50.959 --> 00:31:56.959
Oftentimes we're asking people what can we do to improve, and therefore we're not getting

00:31:57.920 --> 00:32:03.680
that some of the traditional methods of examining sentiment does not allow us to get really good

00:32:03.680 --> 00:32:10.000
sentiment from that. In other words, when employees are making suggestions for improvement, they could

00:32:10.000 --> 00:32:17.920
consist of a combination of positive and negative sentiment, and so we've kind of have not been

00:32:17.920 --> 00:32:23.280
using sentiment analysis specifically in the traditional sense of analyzing all comments

00:32:23.280 --> 00:32:28.560
and saying, is this one positive or is this one negative? We focus more on looking at what are some

00:32:28.560 --> 00:32:33.439
of the common themes or suggestions that we're getting out of that. What are some of the common

00:32:33.439 --> 00:32:37.920
concerns that we are seeing among our employees instead of looking at are they positive or

00:32:37.920 --> 00:32:44.079
negative? Now, on the other hand, we have some surveys are done by vendors, and I don't have

00:32:44.079 --> 00:32:48.800
knowledge of how they go about analyzing their data to determine the sentiment.

00:32:49.599 --> 00:32:55.439
They keep that since it's proprietary to them, and it was developed in within their company.

00:32:55.439 --> 00:32:59.520
They don't share that much. Gotcha. Okay, thank you.

00:33:03.119 --> 00:33:07.599
The lots of great questions coming in here.

00:33:07.599 --> 00:33:14.000
Let's see. Emma had a question a bit earlier on what are your forecasting models of choice

00:33:14.000 --> 00:33:22.079
for time series, and I wasn't sure if we covered that yet. I don't think we have. I have found

00:33:22.959 --> 00:33:30.640
many times exponential smoothing works very well for many of the cases and in cases where I've

00:33:30.640 --> 00:33:36.239
tested different types of algorithms. That one is often turned out to be the most accurate,

00:33:36.800 --> 00:33:42.719
but I will choose a few different methods to test and see which one works out well.

00:33:44.400 --> 00:33:49.199
We don't have a lot of seasonality in our time series. At least I haven't run into a case yet

00:33:49.199 --> 00:33:56.719
with that, but it's something that I do check for when I first start any new project for a specific

00:33:56.719 --> 00:34:03.280
business unit and see if that's something I need to consider in doing my model. So I haven't had

00:34:03.280 --> 00:34:07.119
much occasion to go into the more complex time series models yet.

00:34:10.239 --> 00:34:16.719
Thank you. I see Jared just put a question in the chat. Who is the analysis customer at AT&T,

00:34:16.719 --> 00:34:20.719
the employee or the HR business partner hiring managers?

00:34:21.040 --> 00:34:30.639
Our analysis customers could be HR executives or business unit leaders who are trying to get

00:34:30.639 --> 00:34:34.639
insights about the workforce in their specific business unit.

00:34:39.679 --> 00:34:50.639
Thank you. Well, I think that's a good question. I don't know. I'm not sure if that's the answer.

00:34:51.360 --> 00:34:58.879
I guess something else that I had wanted to ask you. Let me jump over to some of my questions

00:34:58.879 --> 00:35:04.080
here. I have a lot of questions coming in all different places, but how do you see

00:35:04.080 --> 00:35:07.439
the role of people analytics evolving in the future?

00:35:10.959 --> 00:35:19.280
I am seeing more and more companies are interested in using analytics and are hiring analytics

00:35:19.280 --> 00:35:26.560
roles. Richard Rose now maintains a website where he posts open people analytics jobs,

00:35:26.560 --> 00:35:31.679
and that has grown tremendously over the past few months. So I'm seeing more and more companies are

00:35:31.679 --> 00:35:37.760
realizing the benefit of analyzing their employee data and using that data to help support business

00:35:37.760 --> 00:35:47.600
decisions. Whereas traditionally, many, many years ago, HR was doing a lot of decisions based on gut

00:35:47.600 --> 00:35:56.560
instinct or specific scenarios from different business leaders. I think we're moving more and

00:35:56.560 --> 00:36:01.760
more away from those gut instinct decisions, and more and more companies are incorporating

00:36:01.760 --> 00:36:09.040
data analysis. And in our case, we eventually grew to the point, I started doing data analysis 20

00:36:09.040 --> 00:36:14.479
years ago, but eventually grew to the point where now we have a central team within AT&T that is

00:36:14.479 --> 00:36:22.560
focused on our people analytics projects. And we have various team members that focus on reports,

00:36:22.560 --> 00:36:27.280
and some that focus on data science and machine learning. I think we're going to

00:36:29.120 --> 00:36:34.800
get more and more efficient and faster at being able to produce those insights to different business

00:36:34.800 --> 00:36:45.520
leaders. And more, I think, just more advanced analytics and more sophisticated analytics, let

00:36:45.520 --> 00:36:51.919
me put it that way. I can see that growing and becoming more commonplace among companies.

00:36:52.719 --> 00:36:59.439
I still meet a lot of people that are just getting started and are just hearing that this is a

00:37:00.239 --> 00:37:03.040
focused field for data and analysis.

00:37:05.439 --> 00:37:12.800
Yeah, I definitely notice a ton of interest on people analytics posts on LinkedIn, or when we put

00:37:13.919 --> 00:37:19.360
your meetup recording up on YouTube, there's a lot of views on it. And so it seems like there's

00:37:19.360 --> 00:37:24.639
a lot of teams that are just starting to get into people analytics. And I was wondering what

00:37:24.639 --> 00:37:30.080
advice do you have for those organizations that are really just starting to explore, implement

00:37:30.080 --> 00:37:38.639
people analytics? I think if you're just starting a team, developing good relationships with

00:37:39.520 --> 00:37:45.840
your other leaders in HR to find out what are their big concerns, what are their pain points where

00:37:46.560 --> 00:37:51.600
we could apply analytics to help solve problems would be a big part of that. And that will help

00:37:51.600 --> 00:37:55.840
you decide what direction you want to take in building your team if you're just getting started.

00:37:56.479 --> 00:38:02.719
And from there, if you can find the HR leaders, if they are in touch with the business units,

00:38:02.719 --> 00:38:07.600
they can also tell you what are the pain points of the different business units. And from there,

00:38:07.600 --> 00:38:15.360
you can decide how large a team you need or what do you need people that specialize in different

00:38:15.360 --> 00:38:19.120
areas and having a good relationship with each of those different business units.

00:38:19.840 --> 00:38:26.399
Since our company is quite large and complex, we found it's very helpful to have people that

00:38:27.199 --> 00:38:33.040
specialize in serving as a liaison with the different teams and different organizations

00:38:33.040 --> 00:38:41.199
within our company. And that helps direct them to the appropriate team. But at the same time,

00:38:41.199 --> 00:38:46.320
they can help get familiar with what are the common problems that this particular business

00:38:46.320 --> 00:38:51.360
unit is known for experiencing? And are we seeing the same things coming up over and over

00:38:51.360 --> 00:38:57.679
again in their requests? And from there, can we be proactive in trying to develop other tools

00:38:57.679 --> 00:39:04.800
to help them answer their questions or solve their problems? And that may be a good place to get

00:39:04.800 --> 00:39:11.919
started. If you are on LinkedIn or any other social media where you can network with other

00:39:11.919 --> 00:39:17.760
people analytics leaders, just within the past two or three years, there have been a lot of

00:39:17.760 --> 00:39:23.360
people analytics meetup groups developing in different cities. And from there, that's been

00:39:23.360 --> 00:39:28.320
a tremendous help to be able to go to those meetings and talk to people in other organizations,

00:39:28.320 --> 00:39:34.560
other companies, to discuss common pain points that we're all experiencing, common solutions

00:39:34.560 --> 00:39:39.600
that different people have developed. And you get a lot of ideas from those meetings as well.

00:39:42.399 --> 00:39:48.080
That's great. Thank you. I noticed there were two questions, maybe two questions over on Slido,

00:39:48.080 --> 00:39:53.040
I'm going to try and combine a little bit. But the anonymous question was,

00:39:54.000 --> 00:40:00.000
there's a lot of worry about how AI can affect job prospects. And to rephrase the question a

00:40:00.000 --> 00:40:06.479
little bit, any thoughts on the forecasting for how advancements in artificial intelligence affect

00:40:06.479 --> 00:40:16.719
hiring? Going back to what we said earlier in relation to large language models, when

00:40:18.959 --> 00:40:25.360
those large language models were introduced within AT&T, there were a lot of discussions of

00:40:26.239 --> 00:40:29.679
what would be the benefit of that and how that would affect people's jobs.

00:40:30.479 --> 00:40:36.800
I think what we've ended up concluding so far is it does help those who use those tools,

00:40:37.360 --> 00:40:43.199
it's helping them become more efficient. It's serving as a great resource to get answers to

00:40:43.199 --> 00:40:49.040
our questions much faster than we could on our own when we were searching Google or whatever

00:40:49.040 --> 00:40:57.040
other tools. And there's the common phrase that a lot of people are saying is your job won't be

00:40:57.040 --> 00:41:04.000
replaced by an AI tool by itself. It has trouble making decisions, especially the human aspect of

00:41:04.000 --> 00:41:10.639
those decisions and ethics and all of the things that factor into the types of decisions that are

00:41:10.639 --> 00:41:17.919
made in human resources. But people using AI will become more efficient, more effective,

00:41:17.919 --> 00:41:24.479
and better able to respond to those questions. I know among our people analytics team, a lot of

00:41:24.479 --> 00:41:30.320
our people that are doing coding and developing reports have found these tools extremely helpful

00:41:30.320 --> 00:41:36.879
in getting answers very quickly and much faster than before. And it's enabled all of us to work

00:41:36.879 --> 00:41:49.360
much faster. Thank you. I see Abigail asked a question, I'll read it out for you, is what are

00:41:49.360 --> 00:41:55.520
tools, packages, or processes do you personally use most often? Or do you use other languages?

00:41:55.520 --> 00:42:04.800
And I think that's the end of it actually. Primarily I use R right now. When I first completed my

00:42:04.800 --> 00:42:11.120
master's program, I alternated between SAS and Python and R and eventually just got to the point

00:42:11.120 --> 00:42:17.679
where I found it was easier to focus on one language instead of trying to translate from

00:42:17.679 --> 00:42:23.520
one to another. And so I'm exclusively an R programmer these days. We have a few other team

00:42:23.520 --> 00:42:32.479
members that work with Python. As far as R packages, I love Tidyverse. Some of the packages

00:42:32.479 --> 00:42:41.600
related specifically to time series forecasting like Feast and Fable. And there is Text Analytics.

00:42:41.600 --> 00:42:46.719
Oh, I can't remember the package names specifically. I'd have to pull them all up to remember them.

00:42:47.280 --> 00:42:53.040
But at this point I've built my own personal library of R code. And so for different types

00:42:53.040 --> 00:42:57.040
of projects, and depending on what the project is, I can usually pull up the code that I've used

00:42:57.040 --> 00:43:06.879
from a previous one, copy and paste, and modify it as needed. Awesome, thank you. I asked this

00:43:06.879 --> 00:43:11.919
question kind of as a joke in the chat, but I was saying how do we get ourselves to show up in the

00:43:11.919 --> 00:43:18.719
data as somebody needing a raise? But more broadly, just thinking like, do you have any advice

00:43:18.719 --> 00:43:23.919
to share with all of us as somebody coming from human resources and people analytics space

00:43:23.919 --> 00:43:30.000
of how to advocate for ourselves when it comes time for career progressions?

00:43:31.919 --> 00:43:39.040
Ah, very good question. In general, I think prepare yourself for that conversation with

00:43:39.040 --> 00:43:46.159
your supervisor. Do some research. These days there's a lot of information available

00:43:46.159 --> 00:43:50.399
on different websites to find out what is the average salary for different types of jobs.

00:43:51.199 --> 00:43:58.879
So you can see whether or not you fall within the expected range in the market. And you can present

00:43:58.879 --> 00:44:05.679
that data to your supervisor as well. And show your accomplishments. Show the benefit to the company

00:44:06.239 --> 00:44:12.879
in terms of how that helped the company in your accomplishments. So instead of just saying,

00:44:12.879 --> 00:44:18.560
I build a report that does this and provides these insights, think more in terms of how did that help

00:44:18.560 --> 00:44:24.879
solve a business problem? Or did you save time, become more efficient in order to

00:44:25.760 --> 00:44:30.560
help our company progress in terms of being able to get more work done, be more productive,

00:44:31.280 --> 00:44:37.199
and things like that. So do your research, be prepared for that conversation, and bring

00:44:37.199 --> 00:44:42.159
all of that in and schedule some uninterrupted time with your supervisor to discuss it.

00:44:45.120 --> 00:44:52.479
Great, thank you. Yannan asked a question a bit earlier. What is the big difference between

00:44:52.479 --> 00:44:58.959
people analytics and other kinds of general data analytics? Any subjective data related to people

00:44:59.919 --> 00:45:05.679
analytics is very dynamic. Is there any challenge to derive a solid insight from that analysis?

00:45:06.320 --> 00:45:11.360
If yet, what is it? A lot thrown into that one question. So let's start with,

00:45:12.000 --> 00:45:17.120
what is the big difference between people analytics and other kinds of general data analytics?

00:45:18.320 --> 00:45:25.600
The biggest difference is when we are analyzing employee data. So we have to constantly keep in

00:45:25.600 --> 00:45:32.959
mind the ethics of what we do with that data. And in our team, we work closely with our legal

00:45:32.959 --> 00:45:41.360
department. We also have a privacy team that can get involved in our projects and has given us

00:45:41.360 --> 00:45:48.639
guidelines as to when are we doing things that, even though there may not be a law against it,

00:45:48.639 --> 00:45:54.800
we feel it could be considered unethical or we just feel this could be an invasion of privacy.

00:45:55.600 --> 00:46:02.560
So it's important to think about those things when analyzing employee data. For example,

00:46:03.120 --> 00:46:09.840
when we're looking at attrition, you wouldn't want to put race and gender in a model because that

00:46:09.840 --> 00:46:15.199
could be leading to a potential situation where you're discriminating against those employees.

00:46:15.840 --> 00:46:20.000
So we're constantly thinking about that. We're also constantly thinking about testing our models

00:46:20.000 --> 00:46:27.199
for bias to see, is it harming any specific group? And I think that's one area that's very

00:46:27.199 --> 00:46:36.000
different from other types of predictive analytics or data science projects where you're not analyzing

00:46:36.000 --> 00:46:42.719
employee data. That's one of the key differences there is we constantly think in terms of,

